    "summary": "Sargon II (r. 722–705 BC) was one of the most successful Neo-Assyrian conquerors, who completed the [[event:3082|Assyrian Conquest Israel]] conquest of the northern Kingdom of Israel (721 BC), campaigning across Urartu, Anatolia, Babylonia, and the Arabian peninsula, and who built the spectacular planned capital city of Dur-Sharrukin ('Fort Sargon,' modern Khorsabad) — one of the most ambitious urban construction projects of the ancient world.\n\nSargon's fall of Samaria and deportation of approximately 27,000 Israelites became the origin of the legend of the 'Lost Ten Tribes of Israel.' His campaigns against Urartu (714 BC) were recorded in a remarkable propagandistic letter to the god Assur describing the campaign in detail — an extraordinary piece of ancient military narrative literature. Dur-Sharrukin, begun around 717 BC and abandoned at his death, was a planned city of extraordinary scale: the palace complex alone covered 10 hectares and was decorated with miles of carved reliefs. Sargon died in battle against the Cimmerians — an unusual death for an Assyrian king whose body was not recovered, which his successors interpreted as a divine punishment requiring propitiatory measures.",
